To run this project on a fresh college PC, you don't need to install everything "from scratch" manually—you just need the core environment. Since your code is already on GitHub, the process is much faster.

Here is the step-by-step checklist to get your project running on a new machine:

1. Install Core Environment
You must have these two things installed on the PC first:

Node.js: Download the LTS version from nodejs.org. This automatically installs npm (Node Package Manager).

Git: Download from git-scm.com so you can clone your code.

2. Clone the Project
Open a terminal (Command Prompt or PowerShell) and navigate to where you want to save the work (e.g., Desktop).

Bash
git clone https://github.com/Dnyaneshsasale/AngularJS-Practical-Complete-Code-Explanation.git
cd AngularJS-Practical-Complete-Code-Explanation
3. Install Global Dependencies
You need the Angular CLI installed globally on the college PC to use the ng commands:

Bash
npm install -g @angular/cli
4. Install Project Dependencies (The "Magic" Step)
When you pushed to GitHub, you didn't push the node_modules folder (which is correct). You must tell the new PC to look at your package.json file and download all the libraries your project needs:

Bash
npm install
Note: This will create a new node_modules folder on the college PC. This step might take a minute or two.

5. Run the Project
Once npm install finishes, you are ready to go:

Bash
ng serve
Open your browser to http://localhost:4200/.
